I mentioned about "magic numbers"…

`0x08`, `3`… there's a few numbers on this line that have no apparent meaning without reading the specs.  (_I_ know `0x08` here is the `M` bit, but a casual reader may not!).  PR #4396 adds a routine that will do the donkey work of converting that option to an unsigned integer so you'd be left with:

```
    otError Message::ReadBlockOptionValues(…)
    {
        uint64_t rawValue;
        OptionIterator iterator;
        // …

        SuccessOrExit(error = iterator.Init(this));
        VerifyOrExit((option = iterator.GetFirstOptionMatching(aBlockType)) != NULL, error = OT_ERROR_NOT_FOUND);
        SuccessOrExit(error = iterator.GetOptionValue(rawValue));

        *aBlockNumber = rawValue >> 4;
        if ((rawValue & 0x08) >> 3 == 1)
        {
            *aMoreBlocks = true;
        }
        *aBlockSize = (otCoapOptionBlockSize)(rawValue & 0x07); // and this should probably be a static_cast<>
    }
```

We cut some repetition, but note the magic numbers still there.

As a counter-example, have a look at this:
https://github.com/vrtsystems/openthread/commit/7f0e7f1b638d3faa7cde49425ebed2f891160a92

There, I've put the magic numbers in a macro which is named.  Arguably, I could do a bit more.  Those last few lines would collapse to this:

```
        *aBlockNumber = OT_COAP_BLOCK_NUM(rawValue);
        *aMoreBlocks = OT_COAP_BLOCK_MORE(rawValue) != 0;
        *aBlockSize = (otCoapOptionBlockSize)(OT_COAP_BLOCK_SZX(rawValue));
```

