We don't use this idiom much, but I recommend using the `else` clause for exactly this reason. The idea is `try` only has what might fail, `except` has error handling, and `else` has the rest of the related logic.

```python
try:
  hash_ = hash(obj)
except TypeError as e:
  raise TypeError("For object with type '{}', error was: {}".format(type(obj).__name__, e))
else:
  type_id = self.to_id(type(obj))
  return (hash_, TypeId(type_id))
```

Stack overflow post explaining why `try-except-else` is good practice and Pythonic: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16138232/is-it-a-good-practice-to-use-try-except-else-in-python.

