I think the main reason for not DRYing this up is that it's not a check that should happen before _every_ route - for example, we don't want this to happen before the `ALL_FACILITIES_PAGE` route itself.

One way it could be dried up slightly would be to create a function that does this check, and then invoke it in each handler function, similar to the unassigned content guard in Learn: https://github.com/learningequality/kolibri/blob/develop/kolibri/plugins/learn/assets/src/routes/index.js#L25

So, in the case that it catches, it returns `true`. E.g.:

```
function facilityParamRequiredGuard(toRoute, next, subtopicName) {
  if (store.getters.userIsMultiFacilityAdmin && !toRoute.params.facility_id) {
    next({
        name: 'ALL_FACILITIES_PAGE',
        params: { subtopicName },
      });
      return true;
  }
}
```

then the handler function in this case simplifies to:
```
handler: (toRoute, fromRoute, next) => {
  if (facilityParamRequiredGuard(toRoute, next, ManageClassPage.name)) {
    return;
  }
  showClassesPage(store, toRoute);
},
```

The other thing this does is use the [return early pattern](https://gomakethings.com/the-early-return-pattern-in-javascript/), which helps to reduce the nesting in functions.

